Abstract = {Perfluoroalkyl substances (PFASs) have been widely used in different
   types of consumer and industrial applications such as surfactants,
   household cleaning products, textiles, carpets, cosmetics, firefighting
   foams, and food packaging because of their good stability and special
   physicochemical properties of hydrophobicity, oleophobicity, high
   temperature resistance, etc. Meanwhile, PFASs are considered an emerging
   organic pollutant due to their persistence and potential toxicity to
   human health. PFASs occur in edible oil, an important component of the
   global diet, mainly in three ways: raw material contamination, process
   contamination, and migration from oil contact materials. Thus, the
   occurrence of PFAS in edible oils has drawn more and more attention in
