Pages = {325-341},
Month = {JAN},
Abstract = {Arsenic, a metalloid that exists by nature, reaches the earth either by
   natural or anthropogenic events and is considered an emerging pollutant.
   The existence of arsenic in soil systems is a fate to the environment
   since it is mobile and being transported to other systems because of its
   bioavailability and speciation process. Arsenic transformation in the
   soil and its thorough understanding of how it enters plant systems are
   crucial. Notably, transporters are responsible for most of the arsenic
   that enters the plant system. Consumption of crops or animals and
   drinking water polluted with arsenic are the prime factors in
   transmitting arsenic to people. Severe adverse effects on humans arise
   as an outcome of long-term contact with arsenic-rich foodstuff and
   water. An effort has been made to outline the several sources and their
   dynamics in the surroundings and health impact on humans in this review.
   In addition, various strategies have been practiced to remove arsenic in
   the soil and water systems is also addressed.},
