@article{ WOS:001145486900002,
Author = {Dong, Shirley M. and Hickman, Lisa C.},
Title = {Current opinion: postpartum urinary disorders},
Journal = {CURRENT OPINION IN OBSTETRICS \& GYNECOLOGY},
Year = {2023},
Volume = {35},
Number = {6},
Pages = {510-516},
Month = {DEC},
Abstract = {Purpose of reviewThe aim of this study was to describe the common
   postpartum urinary sequelae including urinary retention and
   incontinence, and to summarize the management of these
   conditions.Despite the high frequency of urinary disorders in
   obstetrics, screening and management protocols are rarely utilized by
   providers. Large variation exists in the literature regarding assessment
   of postpartum urinary retention, values of postvoid residuals and
   management of indwelling catheters in the immediate postpartum
   population. Recent expert guidance outlines a strategy for managing this
   condition.Research also highlights that screening for peripartum urinary
   incontinence is not a routine practice. The diagnosis is made more
   challenging by the fact that patients commonly understate and
   over-normalize their symptoms. Emerging studies have found that pelvic
   floor muscle training is cost-effective, preventive, and may improve
   symptoms in the postpartum setting.Increased awareness of urinary
   disorders in pregnancy and postpartum is imperative for appropriate
   diagnosis and management. Instituting standardized voiding protocols
   postpartum will allow providers to avoid undiagnosed postpartum urinary
   retention and its repercussions. Improved screening and education
   regarding urinary incontinence in the peripartum is important for early
   management, such as pelvic floor muscle training, and improved quality
   of life.Papers of particular interest, published within the annual
   period of review, have been highlighted as:While society places a large
   emphasis on antepartum obstetrical care, there continues to be
   insufficient patient education and awareness about the fourth trimester,
   or the first 12 weeks after giving birth, including the many short and
   long-term sequalae associated with delivery. Notably, education about
   peripartum pelvic floor disorders (PFDs) is often ignored during
   pregnancy, with studies finding that patients between the ages of 19 and
   39 years were the least proficient regarding the topic {[}1]. PFDs are
   associated with decreased quality of life, psychological strain and a
   sense of patient embarrassment {[}2]. Out of the three domains of PFDs,
   urinary symptom distress is the most common in obstetrics, with 41.8\%
   of patients reporting these issues {[}2]. These symptoms may present at
   opposite ends of the spectrum during the postpartum period with urinary
   retention and urinary incontinence. As such, the purpose of this article
   is to educate providers on how to prevent, recognize and manage
   postpartum urinary sequelae. no caption availableGenitourinary system
   changes associated with pregnancy begin in the first trimester. The
   underlying mechanisms contributing to these dynamic changes are
   multifaceted. Elevation in the level of progesterone may lead to
   decreased urethral pressures, relaxation of urinary system smooth muscle
   and impaired detrusor contractility {[}3]. Renal changes include an
   increase in glomerular filtration rates and dilation of the ureters,
   resulting in increased urine production and functional bladder volumes.
   The enlarging gravid uterus contributes to bladder compression and can
   lead to urinary frequency, urgency and incontinence {[}2,4]. Together,
   these genitourinary system changes make bladder control issues a common
   phenomenon antepartum, and for some, persistent postpartum.Aspects of
   the birthing process are thought to predispose some individuals to the
   development of urinary disorders as well. Mechanical forces from pushing
   cause anatomical changes with inevitable bladder descent and
   compression.
