   and the act of remedying imbalances of Qi, a concept of the vital force
   of life. Recent small studies involving acupuncture postpartum and
   auricular acupressure are protective against PUR {[}22,23].Urinary
   incontinence, encompassing stress, urge and mixed subtypes, is known to
   have a significant impact on quality of life {[}24]. It is estimated to
   impact 32-64\% of pregnancies and 15-30\% of individuals in the first
   year postpartum {[}25]. Risk factors for postpartum urinary incontinence
   include protracted second stage of labor, operative vaginal delivery,
   increased maternal parity, and larger fetal head circumference {[}4].
   While physiologic factors such as intra-abdominal pressure from a gravid
   uterus may resolve with delivery, limited research exists regarding
   prevention and management of postpartum urinary
   incontinence.Additionally, surveys have shown that a majority of
   patients who report stress urinary incontinence (SUI) antepartum and 8
   weeks postpartum had persistent symptoms 1 year postpartum, highlighting
   the symptom's high positive predictive value {[}26].
   With knowledge that pregnancy is a strong risk factor for urinary
   incontinence and development of pregnancy urinary incontinence is
   strongly associated with persistent symptoms, improved management of
   postpartum urinary incontinence is necessary to reduce the burden it has
   on patients.Similar to PUR, postpartum urinary incontinence lacks
   standardized identification antepartum and postpartum. Studies have
   found that providers do not routinely screen for PFD or urinary
   incontinence complaints in the postpartum period {[}9]. Additionally,
   there is no postpartum-specific screening tool established {[}2,27,28].
   Simple questions such as ``Do you experience bothersome leakage of
   urine?{''} may effectively screen patients and allow providers to avoid
   over-normalization of peripartum urinary incontinence {[}9]. This
   education helps prevent the patient perception that their urinary
   incontinence will improve spontaneously with time, an outcome which not
   every patient may experience {[}27].Lastly, frequent screening may also
   lead to improved outcomes through earlier diagnosis of urinary
   incontinence.In general, pregnancy-related urinary incontinence
   management should focus on conservative efforts including behavioral
   modifications and pelvic floor muscle training (PFMT) with the option of
   including biofeedback. Behavioral modifications include maintaining
   appropriate bladder hygiene with limited bladder irritants and timed
   voids.Following education on behavioral modifications, PFMT is a
   first-line recommendation for management of stress and mixed urinary
   incontinence that remains well tolerated and effective in pregnant and
   postpartum patients {[}24]. A Cochrane review of 46 studies highlighted
   that early, structured antenatal PFMT reduced the risk of late pregnancy
   and postpartum urinary incontinence between 3 and 6 months postpartum in
   patients who were continent prior to pregnancy {[}29]. The ability for
   PFMT to both prevent and treat urinary incontinence may also be
   cost-effective; an additional meta-analysis found that antenatal PFMT
   continued to have risk-reduction for postnatal urinary incontinence
   {[}30]. This factor is important to consider while patients seek PFMT
   during their peripartum period, as many individuals must consider the
   cost of attending additional appointments antenatally. Studies have also
   found additional benefits of a simple antepartum PFMT regimen suggested
   by Woodley and Hay-Smith {[}31] as listed in Table 3, including improved
   sexual satisfaction, prevention anal insufficiency and also improving
   labor and delivery outcomes given overall increased strength and control
   of the pelvic floor musculature.Minimum PFMT exercise
   prescriptionPreviously published in Woodley and Hay-Smith
   {[}31].Pessaries and other vaginal inserts for SUI are additional well
   tolerated options for pregnant and postpartum patients.
   Postpartum-specific pessaries have shown improvement in urinary
   incontinence symptoms at both 3 and 6-month postpartum {[}32]. Specific
   postpartum pessaries such as the Restifem have been utilized as early as
   6 weeks postpartum {[}32]. However, earlier use in a symptomatic patient
   could be considered for patients with minimal or no vaginal tearing from
   the obstetric delivery (including cesarean section) and would be at the
   discretion of the obstetric provider. While pharmacologic therapies such
   as antimuscarinics, beta-3 adrenergics and onabotulinum toxin are an
   option for overactive bladder, they are contraindicated if a patient is
   breastfeeding, limiting their clinical utility for refractory symptoms
   postpartum.
   Lastly, surgical procedures for significant, bothersome SUI are
   typically deferred until a patient heals completely from pregnancy,
   traditionally not before 6 months postpartum.In sum, maternal care
   providers should implement screening for urinary incontinence and offer
   either education on self-taught PFMT regimens or referrals to physical
   therapists for PFMT sessions. Future considerations may utilize
   telemedicine or mobile applications in order to make education regarding
   patient-driven PFMT available at a patient's convenience.When evaluating
   postpartum urinary incontinence, obstetric-related vesicovaginal
   fistulas (VVFs) may be considered. Although rare in developed countries,
   VVFs may occur in the setting of prolonged obstructed labor and often
   present 1-2 weeks after delivery {[}33]. Case reports also report a
   higher incidence of other genitourinary fistulas including vesicouterine
   fistulas in the setting of the increasing incidence of cesarean sections
   {[}34]. Thin lower uterine segments in conjunction with bladder adhesive
   disease and poor visualization of the vesicouterine flexure are likely
   the cause behind these rare fistulas {[}34]. Lastly, a handful of case
   reports have also highlighted genitourinary fistulas in the setting of
   uterine artery embolization for postpartum hemorrhage {[}35]. While all
   of these scenarios are rare, genitourinary fistulas must be considered
   if patients present with atypical symptoms such as continuous clear
   vaginal leakage. These typically can be clinically diagnosed with urine
   pooling in the vagina on a speculum examination; however, a double dye
   tampon test can be helpful if physical examination findings are
   equivocal. Additional imaging, such as a computed tomography (CT)
   urogram, is also important given the elevated incidence of concurrent
   vesicovaginal and ureterovaginal fistulas.Postpartum urinary dysfunction
   is a common sequalae during the immediate postpartum and fourth
   trimester periods. Simple modifications during recovery may reduce PUR
   risk. Using standardized PUR protocols allows for management in both the
   outpatient and inpatient settings and reduces the likelihood of bladder
   injury. Management of peripartum urinary incontinence necessitates early
   identification and utilization of conservative measures such as PFMT.
   Importantly, increased patient and provider education is imperative to
   raise awareness that bladder complaints should be standardly integrated
   in postpartum care.None.},
